<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>POWER STEERING GEAR: TRW/ROSS-TAS 40, 55, 65 AND 85 - INPUT SHAFT SEAL</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec id="hl0500302">
        <title>INPUT SHAFT SEAL</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="10">
            <title>REMOVE</title>
            <para>This procedure uses the vehicle's power steering pump to force out the input shaft seal. To use this
                procedure, the power steering pump should have a minimum of 1,500 psi available.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Block rear wheels and apply parking brake.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect return line from the steering gear and plug the line. Also cap the return
                    port of the gear with a high pressure fitting (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500304">Figure 4</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500304" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500304" filename="../figg05/G0500304.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the steering column from the gear input shaft (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500305">Figure 5</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500305" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500305" filename="../figg05/G0500305.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 5. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the dirt and water seal from the steering gear (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500306">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500306" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500306" filename="../figg05/G0500306.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Wipe out the grease and then remove the spiral retaining ring. Use a screwdriver
                    inserted into the notch formed in the end of the ring. Be careful not to scratch the bore with the
                    screwdriver (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500307">Figure 7</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500307" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500307" filename="../figg05/G0500307.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Slip the steering column back onto the input shaft with the pinch bolt installed, but
                    not tightened (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500308">Figure 8</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500308" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500308" filename="../figg05/G0500308.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 8. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tie or wrap a shop towel around the input shaft area and place a drip pan under the
                    vehicle to catch the oil (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500309">Figure 9</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500309" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500309" filename="../figg05/G0500309.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 9. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Add fluid as necessary, to the full line on the dipstick (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500310">Figure 10</hotlnk>). Do not mix fluid types.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500310" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500310" filename="../figg05/G0500310.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Any mixture of fluid types, or use of any unapproved fluid could lead to seal
                            deterioration and leaks. A leak could ultimately cause the loss of fluid, which could result
                            in a loss of power steering assist.
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the vehicle in neutral, momentarily turn the starter (quickly turn off the engine
                    if it starts). This should pop the input shaft seal out of the housing. Repeat this procedure if the
                    seal fails to pop on the first try.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the shop towel. Disconnect the steering column, and remove the input shaft seal (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500311">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500311" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500311" filename="../figg05/G0500311.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 11. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the seal area of the valve housing for any seal fragments. Remove any that are
                    found (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500312">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500312" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500312" filename="../figg05/G0500312.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 12. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the seal for heat damage (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500313">Figure 13</hotlnk>). If the seal is stiff and brittle, and not pliable
                    like the new seal, it is probably heat damaged. Determine and fix the cause of excessive heat in the
                    steering system.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500313" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500313" filename="../figg05/G0500313.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 13. Input Shaft Seal Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
